IV written in Paris on 17 August 1745: <i id="mwBhc">Your holiness will pardon the liberty taken by one of the lowest of the faithful, though a zealous admirer of virtue, of submitting to the head of the true religion this performance, written in opposition to the founder of a false and barbarous sect. To whom could I with more propriety inscribe a satire on the cruelty and errors of a false prophet, than to the vicar and representative of a God of truth and mercy? Your holiness will therefore give me leave to lay at your feet both the piece and the author of it, and humbly to request your protection of the one, and your benediction upon the other; in hopes of which, with the profoundest reverence, I kiss your sacred feet.</i></span></li><li about="#cite_note-191" id="cite_note-191"><a href="./Voltaire#cite_ref-191" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-191" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt612" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"title":{"wt":"German Literature on the Middle East: Discourses and Practices, 1000–1989"},"publisher":{"wt":"University of Michigan Press"},"year":{"wt":"2011"},"first":{"wt":"Nina"},"last":{"wt":"Berman"},"page":{"wt":"118"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBhg">Berman, Nina (2011). <i id="mwBhk">German Literature on the Middle East: Discourses and Practices, 1000–1989</i>. University of Michigan Press. p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwBho"> </span>118.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=German+Literature+on+the+Middle+East%3A+Discourses+and+Practices%2C+1000%E2%80%931989&amp;rft.pages=118&amp;rft.pub=University+of+Michigan+Press&amp;rft.date=2011&amp;rft.aulast=Berman&amp;rft.aufirst=Nina&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AVoltaire" class="Z3988" about="#mwt612" id="mwBhs"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt612" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwBhw"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-192" id="cite_note-192"><a href="./Voltaire#cite_ref-192" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-192" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt613" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"title":{"wt":"The Concept of Human Dignity in the French and American Enlightenments: Religion, Virtue, Liberty"},"year":{"wt":"2006"},"quote":{"wt":"Voltaire goes on to accuse other religions such as Islam for their own intolerance (359). Voltaire, then, seems to consider Christianity as one of many intolerant and absurd religions."},"page":{"wt":"280"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBh0"><i id="mwBh4">The Concept of Human Dignity in the French and American Enlightenments: Religion, Virtue, Liberty</i>. 2006. p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwBh8"> </span>280. <q id="mwBiA">Voltaire goes on to accuse other religions such as Islam for their own intolerance (359). Voltaire, then, seems to consider Christianity as one of many intolerant and absurd religions.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Concept+of+Human+Dignity+in+the+French+and+American+Enlightenments%3A+Religion%2C+Virtue%2C+Liberty&amp;rft.pages=280&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AVoltaire" class="Z3988" about="#mwt613" id="mwBiE"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt613" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"